This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring April 14, 2012, as Pan American Day and April 8 through April 14, 2012, as Pan American Week. The proclamation celebrates the legacy of international partnership and cooperation in the Americas. It emphasizes the United States' commitment to working together with other countries in the region to create social and economic opportunities, ensure safety, build democratic institutions, and secure a clean energy future. The proclamation also highlights recent achievements, such as the implementation of Free Trade Agreements with Panama and Colombia, and initiatives to promote education and innovation. The article concludes with a mention of the Sixth Summit of the Americas in Cartagena, Colombia, where leaders will gather to discuss progress and reaffirm their commitment to the prosperity and security of all people in the Americas.